cs.FL, cs.DS, cs.IT, cs.LO, cs.CC. 

The paper deals with the computational power of periodically iterated morphisms, which are closely related to formal languages and automata theory. Therefore, cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the construction of a PD0L word with exponential subword complexity, which is related to the study of combinatorics on words, making cs.DS (Discrete Mathematics) a likely sub-category as well. The use of Fractran, a programming language as powerful as Turing Machines, suggests that the paper may also belong to cs.IT (Information Theory) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the undecidability results in the paper involve logical and decision-theoretic questions, which may place it in the sub-category cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science).
